specification: Tapadera; The rump is composed of the last loin bone, hip bone, sacrum, muscles and other tissues.

Punta y pecho; The point end brisket is composed of the sternum, five ribs, muscles and other tissues. It is separated from the forequarter by the removal of the neck cranially, the chuck dorsally, and the plate caudally. This is the chest of the carcass.
Cut from the hindquarter, known for leanness and flavor
Kadera sa Unahan; The chuck is composed of the first five backbones, first five ribs, muscles and other tissues, commonly used for stews and ground beef.
Cut from the back of the cow, known for tenderness and versatility
The most tender cut, often used for steaks
Cut from the short loin, ideal for grilling

Kamto; The flank is composed of a rib, muscles and other tissues of the abdomen. It is separated from the hindquarter by cutting its tip from the medial side of the round 45° towards the tip of the hip bone.
From the rib section, prized for marbling and flavor
The forequarter is the anterior portion of the beef side which is separated from the hindquarter by a cut usually passing
Paypay at Kenchi sa Unahan; The front limb is composed of the shoulder blade, arm, and front shank bones, muscles and other tissues.
Kadera sa Hulihan; The rib set is composed of the last seven back (thoracic) bones, seven ribs, muscles and other tissues.
Tadyang; The plate is composed of the last seven ribs, navel end brisket, muscles, and other tissues.

Tagiliran; The loin is composed of the last backbone, first five loin bones, muscles and other tissues. The tenderloin is or may be separated first from the loin and rump by cutting along the base of the hip bone towards the wings of the loin bones down to the last backbone.
Meat from the front quarter of Buffalo, often used for stewing
Leftover meat pieces after primary cuts
Includes hindquarter, steaks, and ground meat
Kasim; The half of the shoulder on the shank side.
Pigue; The hind leg is derived from the side of a pork carcass after its attachment to the middle,
Liempo; The belly is prepared from the middle by the removal of the loin, cut approximately 2 inches - 3 inches from and parallel to the bodies of the thoracic and lumbar vertebrae.
Lomo; The loin is prepared from the middle by making a cut approximately 2 inches –3 inches from the body of the thoracic vertebrae, thus, separating the belly.
Pata Unahan; The foreshank and foot is prepared from the shoulder by cutting it just above the elbow joint.

Paypay; The whole shoulder is derived from a side of pork carcass by a cut between the 4th and 5th ribs; the cut is extended ventrally following the contour of the ribs, and dorsally at the junction between the 4th and 5th thoracic vertebrae (backbone).
Pata Hulihan; The hind shank and foot is prepared from the hind leg by cutting it through the stifle joint (knee joint).
Ulo; A head is derived from a carcass by cutting through the vertebral column in a straight line through the atlas joint (atlanto occipital joint).
Shoulder, legs, chops, and ground lamb
